So question is:

Protego has been contracted to do a network infrastructure test as part of a broader penetration testing engagement. What will you be targeting in this test? (Choose three.)

AAA servers

IPS devices

virtual machines (VM) that are running in the cloud

the digital storefront

switches

So under a network test we test AAA servers, IPS devices, and switches. What are these?
AAA servers: (Authentication, Authorization, Accounting)
Authentication: This part of the system will check my "IDs"...like my username, password, fingerprints, ip, maybe mac adress, everything which can identify the user, thats its really me...
Authorization: This will check what can i do, what are my privileges....am i an administrator, or a ceo, or just a simple user.
Accounting:This system will record everything what i did after i joined to the network. Like i deleted smthing, copied smthing...etc.

There is 2 main protocolls:
RADIUS and TACACS+. 
Radius (Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service) is the mainly used, we use it for wifi, VPN, etc. 
TACACS+ (Terminal Access Controller Access-Control System Plus) is created by Cisco, it more secure then radius, it hashes the whole communication, not just the password, and its separates the authentication from the authorization.
These are the "brains" of the whole network, if a hacker once break in, he can acces to anything what is on the network (routers, switches...anything)

IPS services:
Intrusion Prevention System...it is a system which monitoring the network 24/7. It detects if something not normal happening, recording it, and tries to stop it automatically.
Its checking every packets on the network, and if an attacker trying to break in, it is automatically disconnecting the attacker, deleting the malicious packets and putting the attacker's ip on a tiltlist.
2 types: NIPS and HIPS. Nips is a network based IPS, hips is a host based IPS. Network based is checking the whole network, host based is only checking one computer or server.
These are the servers whose are vulnerale to ddos attacks...too much packets can freeze the detecting system...

Solution is AAA, IPS, switches.

